page.title: 04FENSIDE
page.content: Fenside is a lonely place, off the beaten track. There are lots of little dykes that run across it into Barton Broad. The roads that run through Fenside are bumpy with grass often growing through the surface. Beside the roads are grazing meadows and fields containing crops. The land drains into Barton Broad. It is lonely to live down here and when it rains the roads and gardens flood. Fenside is a good place for fishing and observing wildlife. It is peaceful and quiet for birds to nest. Butterflies, moths and gnats are common during the summer months. Other insects live here too, such as hornets and dragonflies. In the woods men shoot wildfowl. It is also a good place for finding a wide variety of wild flowers.
